Object-Oriented Project ManagementKenneth Rubin & Adele Goldberg, ParcPlace
Object-oriented projects have to be managed properly to obtainthe most benefits from object-oriented technology. This tutorialexplains the effect of object-oriented technology on costs,staffing and choice of methodology. It describes the pitfalls thatattend object-oriented projects so that you can avoid them, andexplains the key processes, including development style, use ofprototyping, and reuse. It gives specific guidelines for organizingprojects, managing a reuse library, estimating the size and cost ofprojects, and introducing object-oriented technology into anorganization.